---
import StudyLayout from '../../../layouts/StudyLayout.astro';
const bodyHtml = `<header>
    <div class="kicker">// CCA-F FIELD MANUAL : SETUP</div>
    <h1>Getting<br>Started</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">Zero to a working line of dialogue with the model. No tools, no loop, no framework. Just Python, the SDK, a key, and one request that comes back with an answer.<span class="blink"></span></p>
  </header>

  <!-- GOAL -->
  <div class="goal">
    <span class="tag">▶ THE GOAL</span>
    <p class="big">By the end of this page you will send <b>one request</b> to Claude and print the reply.</p>
    <p class="sub">That single round-trip is the foundation. Tools, loops, and agents all sit on top of this exact call.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- WHAT YOU NEED -->
  <section class="step" id="need" style="border-top:none;padding-top:20px;">
    <div class="step-head"><h2 style="color:var(--neon-amber)">What You Need</h2></div>
    <p class="lead">Three things. That is the whole list.</p>
    <div class="need">
      <div class="need-item">
        <div class="ni">01</div>
        <h3 class="glow-am">Python 3.9+</h3>
        <p>The SDK requires Python 3.9 or newer. We install and verify it in Step 1.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="need-item">
        <div class="ni">02</div>
        <h3 class="glow-am">An API key</h3>
        <p>A secret string from the Anthropic Console that authorizes your requests. Step 2.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="need-item">
        <div class="ni">03</div>
        <h3 class="glow-am">A terminal</h3>
        <p>Terminal on Mac/Linux, PowerShell on Windows. Where you run every command below.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- STEP 1: PYTHON -->
  <section class="step" id="s1">
    <div class="step-head"><span class="step-num">01</span><h2>Install Python</h2></div>
    <p class="lead">Pick your OS. After installing, the verify command should print a version of 3.9 or higher.</p>

    <div class="os-tabs" data-group="py">
      <button class="os-tab active" data-os="mac">macOS</button>
      <button class="os-tab" data-os="win">Windows</button>
      <button class="os-tab" data-os="linux">Linux</button>
      <button class="os-tab" data-os="winbash">Git Bash</button>
    </div>

    <div class="os-panel active" data-group="py" data-os="mac">
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">Terminal — macOS</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c"># Install Homebrew first if you don't have it, then:</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> brew install python

<span class="c"># Verify</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> python3 --version
<span class="c"># -> Python 3.12.x</span></code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="os-panel" data-group="py" data-os="win">
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">PowerShell — Windows</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c"># Easiest: install from python.org and CHECK</span>
<span class="c"># "Add python.exe to PATH" during the installer.</span>
<span class="c"># Or via winget:</span>
<span class="prompt">&gt;</span> winget install Python.Python.3.12

<span class="c"># Verify (restart PowerShell first)</span>
<span class="prompt">&gt;</span> python --version
<span class="c"># -> Python 3.12.x</span></code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="os-panel" data-group="py" data-os="linux">
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">Terminal — Linux (Debian/Ubuntu)</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="prompt">$</span> sudo apt update
<span class="prompt">$</span> sudo apt install python3 python3-venv python3-pip

<span class="c"># Verify</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> python3 --version
<span class="c"># -> Python 3.12.x</span></code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="os-panel" data-group="py" data-os="winbash">
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">Git Bash — Windows</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c"># Install Python the Windows way first (see the Windows tab):</span>
<span class="c"># python.org installer or "winget install Python.Python.3.12".</span>
<span class="c"># Once installed system-wide, Python is available in git bash too.</span>

<span class="c"># Verify (restart git bash after the install)</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> python --version
<span class="c"># -> Python 3.12.x</span></code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="why"><b>Why:</b> the <code>anthropic</code> package targets Python 3.9 and up. Anything older will fail to install or import.</div>
  </section>

  <!-- STEP 2: API KEY -->
  <section class="step" id="s2">
    <div class="step-head"><span class="step-num">02</span><h2>Get Your API Key</h2></div>
    <p class="lead">Create a key in the Anthropic Console. This is what proves a request is yours and bills it to your account.</p>
    <ol style="list-style:none;">
      <li class="lead">→ Go to <a href="https://console.anthropic.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">console.anthropic.com</a> and sign in.</li>
      <li class="lead">→ Open <span class="glow-cy">Settings → API Keys</span> and create a new key.</li>
      <li class="lead">→ Copy it now. It looks like <code class="glow-mg">sk-ant-...</code> and is shown only once.</li>
    </ol>
    <div class="warn"><b>⚠ Keep it secret.</b> Never paste your key into code you will commit, share, or post. We load it from an environment variable in Step 4 so it stays out of your files.</div>
    <div class="why"><b>Why:</b> a leaked key lets anyone spend against your account. Environment variables keep the secret in your shell session, not in source control.</div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!-- STEPS 3 + 4: Create venv & Install SDK (two paths)            -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section class="step" id="venv-intro">
    <div class="step-head"><h2>Create a Virtual Environment</h2></div>
    <p class="lead">A venv is an isolated sandbox for this project's packages, so the SDK does not collide with anything else on your machine. Create it once, then activate it whenever you work. Without one, <code>pip install</code> would dump packages into your system Python and cause version conflicts across projects.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="paths-intro">
    <p><strong class="glow-cy">▶ PICK ONE PATH.</strong> Use the venv + pip path on the left <em>or</em> the uv path on the right, <b class="glow-am">not both</b>, then continue with Step 5 below. Both venv + pip and uv are ways to get from "no project folder" to "SDK installed". The exam path likely expects venv + pip knowledge, so learn that if you do not know it.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="paths">
  <!-- LEFT: VENV + PIP PATH -->
  <div class="path">
    <span class="path-tag">▶ VENV + PIP PATH</span>

    <!-- 03 inside venv path -->
    <div class="path-step">
      <div class="path-step-head"><span class="step-num">03</span><h3>Create the venv</h3></div>

      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">create the venv</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c"># Make a project folder and step into it</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> mkdir <span class="glow-mg">claude-start</span> && cd <span class="glow-mg">claude-start</span>

<span class="c"># Create the virtual environment named .venv</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> python3 -m venv .venv</code></pre>
      </div>
      <p class="lead" style="margin-top:10px;font-size:0.84rem;"><span class="glow-mg">claude-start</span> is just the folder name — call it whatever you want (<code>my-agent</code>, <code>cca-prep</code>, etc.). Both commands use the same name; if you change one, change both.</p>

      <p class="lead" style="margin-top:18px;">Activation is the one command that differs per OS:</p>

      <div class="os-tabs" data-group="venv">
        <button class="os-tab active" data-os="mac">macOS</button>
        <button class="os-tab" data-os="win">Windows</button>
        <button class="os-tab" data-os="linux">Linux</button>
        <button class="os-tab" data-os="winbash">Git Bash</button>
      </div>

      <div class="os-panel active" data-group="venv" data-os="mac">
        <div class="code">
          <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">activate — macOS (zsh/bash)</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="prompt">$</span> source .venv/bin/activate

<span class="c"># Your prompt now shows (.venv)</span>
<span class="c">(.venv) $</span></code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="os-panel" data-group="venv" data-os="win">
        <div class="code">
          <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">activate — Windows (PowerShell)</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="prompt">&gt;</span> .venv\\Scripts\\Activate.ps1

<span class="c"># If blocked by execution policy, run once:</span>
<span class="prompt">&gt;</span> Set-ExecutionPolicy -Scope CurrentUser RemoteSigned

<span class="c"># Prompt now shows (.venv)</span>
<span class="c">(.venv) &gt;</span></code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="os-panel" data-group="venv" data-os="linux">
        <div class="code">
          <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">activate — Linux (bash)</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="prompt">$</span> source .venv/bin/activate

<span class="c"># Your prompt now shows (.venv)</span>
<span class="c">(.venv) $</span></code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="os-panel" data-group="venv" data-os="winbash">
        <div class="code">
          <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">activate — Git Bash (Windows)</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c"># Note: Scripts/ (not bin/) on Windows, but source still works in git bash:</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> source .venv/Scripts/activate

<span class="c"># Your prompt now shows (.venv)</span>
<span class="c">(.venv) $</span></code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- 04 inside venv path -->
    <div class="path-step">
      <div class="path-step-head"><span class="step-num">04</span><h3>Install the SDK</h3></div>
      <p class="lead">One command, same on every OS. Run it with your venv active.</p>
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">install anthropic</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c">(.venv) $</span> pip install anthropic

<span class="c"># Confirm it landed</span>
<span class="c">(.venv) $</span> pip show anthropic</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <!-- /VENV + PIP PATH -->

  <!-- RIGHT: MODERN ALTERNATIVE (uv) -->
  <div class="alt">
    <span class="alt-tag">▶ MODERN ALTERNATIVE</span>
    <h3 class="alt-h3">Use <code class="glow-mg">uv</code> instead of venv + pip</h3>
    <p class="alt-head"><a href="https://docs.astral.sh/uv/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">uv</a> is a single Rust-based tool from Astral that replaces <code>venv</code> and <code>pip</code>, much faster than both.</p>

    <p class="lead" style="margin-top:14px;">Install uv first — the command differs per OS:</p>

    <div class="os-tabs" data-group="uv-install">
      <button class="os-tab active" data-os="mac">macOS</button>
      <button class="os-tab" data-os="win">Windows</button>
      <button class="os-tab" data-os="linux">Linux</button>
      <button class="os-tab" data-os="winbash">Git Bash</button>
    </div>

    <div class="os-panel active" data-group="uv-install" data-os="mac">
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">install uv — macOS</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="prompt">$</span> curl -LsSf https://astral.sh/uv/install.sh | sh</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="os-panel" data-group="uv-install" data-os="win">
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">install uv — Windows (PowerShell)</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="prompt">&gt;</span> powershell -c <span class="s">"irm https://astral.sh/uv/install.ps1 | iex"</span></code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="os-panel" data-group="uv-install" data-os="linux">
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">install uv — Linux</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="prompt">$</span> curl -LsSf https://astral.sh/uv/install.sh | sh</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="os-panel" data-group="uv-install" data-os="winbash">
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">install uv — Git Bash (Windows)</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c"># git bash has curl, so the Unix installer works here too:</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> curl -LsSf https://astral.sh/uv/install.sh | sh</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- 03 inside uv path -->
    <div class="path-step">
      <div class="path-step-head"><span class="step-num">03</span><h3>Create the venv</h3></div>

      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">create the venv</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c"># Make a project folder and step into it</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> mkdir <span class="glow-mg">claude-start</span> && cd <span class="glow-mg">claude-start</span>

<span class="c"># Create the virtual environment named .venv</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> uv venv</code></pre>
      </div>

      <p class="lead" style="margin-top:18px;">Activation is identical to the venv + pip column (same <code>source .venv/bin/activate</code> on mac/linux, <code>.venv\\Scripts\\Activate.ps1</code> on Windows).</p>

      <p class="lead" style="margin-top:14px;font-size:0.84rem;"><b class="glow-mg">Skip activation entirely</b> with project mode: <code>uv init <span class="glow-mg">claude-start</span></code> creates a folder with a <code>pyproject.toml</code> + venv, and <code>uv run</code> later uses that venv automatically.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 04 inside uv path -->
    <div class="path-step">
      <div class="path-step-head"><span class="step-num">04</span><h3>Install the SDK</h3></div>
      <p class="lead">One command, much faster than pip. Run it with your venv active.</p>
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">install anthropic</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c">(.venv) $</span> uv pip install anthropic</code></pre>
      </div>
      <p class="lead" style="margin-top:14px;font-size:0.84rem;">In <b class="glow-mg">project mode</b>: <code>uv add anthropic</code> instead — records it in <code>pyproject.toml</code> + <code>uv.lock</code>.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <!-- /MODERN ALTERNATIVE -->
  </div>
  <!-- /paths -->

  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!-- STEP 5: Set Your API Key (two paths)                          -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <section class="step" id="key-intro">
    <div class="step-head"><span class="step-num">05</span><h2>Set Your API Key</h2></div>
    <p class="lead">The SDK automatically reads an environment variable named <code class="glow-cy">ANTHROPIC_API_KEY</code>. There are two ways to put it there: a shell export or a <code>.env</code> file. Either way, the key never appears in your <code>.py</code> file, which is what keeps <code>hello_claude.py</code> safe to commit or share.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="paths-intro">
    <p><strong class="glow-cy">▶ PICK ONE PATH.</strong> Shell export on the left is fastest for one-off testing. The <code>.env</code> file on the right is better for projects you will come back to, especially with multiple keys.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="paths">
  <!-- LEFT: SHELL ENV PATH -->
  <div class="path">
    <span class="path-tag">▶ SHELL ENV PATH</span>

    <p class="lead">Set the variable in your shell. The command differs per OS:</p>

    <div class="os-tabs" data-group="key">
      <button class="os-tab active" data-os="mac">macOS</button>
      <button class="os-tab" data-os="win">Windows</button>
      <button class="os-tab" data-os="linux">Linux</button>
      <button class="os-tab" data-os="winbash">Git Bash</button>
    </div>

    <div class="os-panel active" data-group="key" data-os="mac">
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">set key — macOS (zsh)</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c"># For this session only:</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> export ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=<span class="s">"sk-ant-your-key-here"</span>

<span class="c"># To persist it, add that line to ~/.zshrc, then:</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> source ~/.zshrc</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="os-panel" data-group="key" data-os="win">
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">set key — Windows (PowerShell)</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c"># For this session only:</span>
<span class="prompt">&gt;</span> $env:ANTHROPIC_API_KEY = <span class="s">"sk-ant-your-key-here"</span>

<span class="c"># To persist across sessions:</span>
<span class="prompt">&gt;</span> setx ANTHROPIC_API_KEY <span class="s">"sk-ant-your-key-here"</span>
<span class="c"># (reopen PowerShell for setx to take effect)</span></code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="os-panel" data-group="key" data-os="linux">
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">set key — Linux (bash)</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c"># For this session only:</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> export ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=<span class="s">"sk-ant-your-key-here"</span>

<span class="c"># To persist it, add that line to ~/.bashrc, then:</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> source ~/.bashrc</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="os-panel" data-group="key" data-os="winbash">
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">set key — Git Bash (Windows)</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c"># For this session only:</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> export ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=<span class="s">"sk-ant-your-key-here"</span>

<span class="c"># To persist it, add that line to ~/.bashrc, then:</span>
<span class="prompt">$</span> source ~/.bashrc</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <!-- /SHELL ENV PATH -->

  <!-- RIGHT: .ENV FILE PATH -->
  <div class="alt">
    <span class="alt-tag">▶ .ENV FILE PATH</span>
    <h3 class="alt-h3">Load it from a <code class="glow-mg">.env</code> file</h3>
    <p class="alt-head">A <code>.env</code> file keeps the key inside the project folder (gitignored), so you do not have to re-export it in every new shell session. Better for projects you will reopen and for juggling multiple keys.</p>

    <p class="lead" style="margin-top:14px;">Install <code class="glow-cy">python-dotenv</code>:</p>
    <div class="code">
      <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">install python-dotenv</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c">(.venv) $</span> pip install python-dotenv</code></pre>
    </div>
    <p class="lead" style="margin-top:8px;font-size:0.84rem;">Using uv? <code>uv pip install python-dotenv</code> (or <code>uv add python-dotenv</code> in project mode).</p>

    <p class="lead" style="margin-top:18px;">Create <code class="glow-cy">.env</code> in your project folder:</p>
    <div class="code">
      <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">.env</span></div>
<pre><code>ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=<span class="s">sk-ant-your-key-here</span></code></pre>
    </div>

    <div class="warn"><b>⚠ Always gitignore <code>.env</code>.</b> Add a line containing <code>.env</code> to your <code>.gitignore</code> so the key is never committed.</div>
  </div>
  <!-- /.ENV FILE PATH -->
  </div>
  <!-- /paths -->

  <!-- STEP 6: WRITE FILE -->
  <section class="step" id="s6">
    <div class="step-head"><span class="step-num">06</span><h2>Write the File</h2></div>
    <p class="lead">Create <code class="glow-cy">hello_claude.py</code> in your project folder. This is the entire program: one request, one printed reply. No tools, no loop.</p>
    <div class="code">
      <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">hello_claude.py</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="k">import</span> anthropic

<span class="c"># Reads ANTHROPIC_API_KEY from your environment automatically</span>
client <span class="k">=</span> anthropic.<span class="f">Anthropic</span>()

resp <span class="k">=</span> client.messages.<span class="f">create</span>(
    model<span class="k">=</span><span class="s">"claude-opus-4-8"</span>,
    max_tokens<span class="k">=</span><span class="n">256</span>,
    messages<span class="k">=</span>[
        {<span class="s">"role"</span>: <span class="s">"user"</span>, <span class="s">"content"</span>: <span class="s">"Say hello and tell me one fact about owls."</span>},
    ],
)

<span class="c"># The reply is a list of content blocks. For a plain text answer,</span>
<span class="c"># the first block holds the text.</span>
<span class="f">print</span>(resp.content[<span class="n">0</span>].text)</code></pre>
    </div>

    <div class="why"><b>Why:</b> <code>anthropic.Anthropic()</code> with no arguments uses the env var key. <code>model</code> picks which Claude answers. <code>max_tokens</code> caps the reply length. <code>messages</code> is the conversation, here a single user turn. <code>resp.content[0].text</code> pulls the text out of the first content block.</div>

    <div class="dotenv-note">
      <p><b class="glow-mg">If you took the <code>.env</code> file path in Step 05,</b> add two lines to the top of <code>hello_claude.py</code> so it reads the file before creating the client:</p>
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">hello_claude.py (add at the top)</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="k">from</span> dotenv <span class="k">import</span> load_dotenv
<span class="f">load_dotenv</span>()  <span class="c"># reads .env into os.environ</span></code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="keyways" style="margin-top:24px;">
      <h3 class="alt-h3">Two ways to give the client your key</h3>
      <p class="lead">Out in the wild you will see the client created either of these ways. They build the <b class="glow-lm">identical</b> client, the only difference is who reads the key out of the environment.</p>

      <p class="lead" style="margin-top:16px;"><b class="glow-mg">Version A, explicit.</b> You fetch the key yourself with <code>os.getenv</code> and hand it to the SDK:</p>
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">explicit key</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="k">import</span> os
<span class="k">from</span> dotenv <span class="k">import</span> load_dotenv
<span class="k">import</span> anthropic

<span class="f">load_dotenv</span>()
client <span class="k">=</span> anthropic.<span class="f">Anthropic</span>(api_key<span class="k">=</span>os.<span class="f">getenv</span>(<span class="s">"ANTHROPIC_API_KEY"</span>))</code></pre>
      </div>

      <p class="lead" style="margin-top:16px;"><b class="glow-cy">Version B, implicit.</b> You let the SDK read the key itself:</p>
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">implicit key</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="k">from</span> dotenv <span class="k">import</span> load_dotenv
<span class="k">import</span> anthropic

<span class="c"># pull ANTHROPIC_API_KEY out of .env so the SDK can read it</span>
<span class="f">load_dotenv</span>()
client <span class="k">=</span> anthropic.<span class="f">Anthropic</span>()</code></pre>
      </div>

      <div class="why"><b>The difference:</b> the SDK's <code>Anthropic()</code> constructor already defaults its <code>api_key</code> to the <code>ANTHROPIC_API_KEY</code> environment variable. Version A does that lookup by hand and passes the result in, Version B lets the SDK do the same lookup. Once <code>load_dotenv()</code> has loaded your <code>.env</code> they see the same key, so Version B also drops the now-unused <code>import os</code>.</div>

      <div class="dotenv-note"><p><b class="glow-lm">The rest of this field manual uses Version B.</b> It is the SDK's intended default, it is less code to read, and the key still never touches the file. Every later page either creates the client this way or assumes a <code>client</code> you already built this way, so once your <code>.env</code> is set up here, those examples run without changes.</p></div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="alt-h3" style="text-transform:none;margin-top:24px;">Why <code>import anthropic</code>, not <code>from anthropic import Anthropic</code>?</h3>
    <p class="lead">Both import styles hand you the same <code>Anthropic</code> class, so this is a style choice, not a behavior change. This manual sticks with <code>import anthropic</code> for three reasons:</p>
    <ul class="reasons">
      <li><b>Namespacing.</b> <code>anthropic.Anthropic()</code> makes it self-evident where the class comes from, no guessing.</li>
      <li><b>Error handling later.</b> If you add a <code>try / except anthropic.APIError:</code>, it is already reachable without touching the imports.</li>
      <li><b>Avoids name clashes.</b> A bare <code>Anthropic</code> could collide with another symbol; the prefixed form never does.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="lead" style="font-size:0.84rem;">It is a defensible choice, but it is not what most Anthropic examples use. The official quickstart usually writes <code>from anthropic import Anthropic</code>, so you will run into that form often too.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- STEP 7: RUN -->
  <section class="step" id="s7">
    <div class="step-head"><span class="step-num">07</span><h2>Run It</h2></div>
    <p class="lead">With your venv active and key set, run the file.</p>

    <div class="os-tabs" data-group="run">
      <button class="os-tab active" data-os="mac">macOS</button>
      <button class="os-tab" data-os="win">Windows</button>
      <button class="os-tab" data-os="linux">Linux</button>
      <button class="os-tab" data-os="winbash">Git Bash</button>
    </div>

    <div class="os-panel active" data-group="run" data-os="mac">
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">run — macOS</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c">(.venv) $</span> python3 hello_claude.py</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="os-panel" data-group="run" data-os="win">
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">run — Windows</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c">(.venv) &gt;</span> python hello_claude.py</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="os-panel" data-group="run" data-os="linux">
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">run — Linux</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c">(.venv) $</span> python3 hello_claude.py</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="os-panel" data-group="run" data-os="winbash">
      <div class="code">
        <div class="code-bar"><span class="dot r"></span><span class="dot y"></span><span class="dot g"></span><span class="fname">run — Git Bash (Windows)</span></div>
<pre><code><span class="c"># Use python (not python3) — Windows Python registers as "python":</span>
<span class="c">(.venv) $</span> python hello_claude.py</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="output">
      <div class="label">// EXPECTED OUTPUT</div>
<pre>Hello! Here's an owl fact: owls can rotate their heads
about 270 degrees because they have extra neck vertebrae
and a specialized blood-flow system that keeps the brain
supplied during the turn.</pre>
    </div>
    <div class="why"><b>Why:</b> if you see a reply, every piece is wired correctly: Python runs, the SDK is installed, the key authorizes you, and the request reached the model and came back. If you get an authentication error, your key is unset or wrong (revisit Step 5).</div>
  </section>

  <!-- DONE -->
  <div class="done-box">
    <h3>// YOU'RE LIVE</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><b>You have a working line to the model.</b> One request in, one reply out. Everything else is built on this exact call.</li>
      <li><b>Your secret stays out of your code.</b> The key lives in an environment variable, so <code>hello_claude.py</code> is safe to share.</li>
      <li><b>Next up:</b> give the model a tool, then wrap the call in a loop so it can act on what the tool returns. That is the agentic loop.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <footer>
    GETTING STARTED // single request, no tools, no loop // model strings update over time, see docs.claude.com<span class="blink"></span>
  </footer>`;
---

